Cook,<br><br>
As I have said all along, I respect your opinion. I just don't agree with it.<br><br>
Nothing that can be said about the testimony can change WHAT I SAW. For people to say that &quot;hearsay doesn't count&quot; is like saying that I didn't see what *I* saw. What is the use in a discussion or dialogue if the participant's statements are seen as just as &quot;hearsay&quot;? Are we to believe only what we want to believe or what is easy and convenient to believe? Do I take the winter soldier testimony as the definitive word? No. But, BASED ON WHAT I WITNESSED, I am not going to dismiss it entirely, either.<br><br>
Of course the NVA could use such testimony as propaganda. But, *I saw* much that also could be used as propaganda. <br><br>
I don't know how long you have been on line, but I will wager that you will run into people who will tell you the things that *they* saw. These people will tell their stories to those who they feel will understand. And not judge.<br><br>

